					<div class=3D"entry-content show-first-item"><p>When it was announced =
that the Harry Potter site <a href=3D"https://my.pottermore.com/patronus" t=
arget=3D"_blank">Pottermore</a> had a new quiz that would reveal your inner=
 patronus, I dropped everything.</p>
<p>Maybe it=E2=80=99s just because I=E2=80=99m a J.K. Rowling fanboy or may=
be sites like Buzzfeed have proven that people just really, really love tak=
ing pop culture quizzes, but, for whatever reason, I was stupidly excited t=
o take the test.</p>
<p>If you=E2=80=99re unfamiliar, a patronus is a kind of ghostly magical gu=
ardian that a wizard or witch can summon, an anthropomorphic animal represe=
ntation of your warmest emotions. Harry Potter=E2=80=99s patronus was a mig=
hty stag. Ginny Weasley had a majestic horse. Albus Dumbledore had a fiery =
phoenix. So I was incredibly curious to see which patronus would represent =
me the best.</p>
<p>Now I=E2=80=99ve had some issues with Pottermore quizzes in the past. Wh=
en I took the <a href=3D"https://my.pottermore.com/sorting-hat" target=3D"_=
blank">Hogwarts sorting test</a>, I was sorted into Hufflepuff =E2=80=94 th=
e Jan Brady of Hogwarts houses =E2=80=94 and, I=E2=80=99m not proud to admi=
t, it took me a long while to be okay with that result.</p>
<p>But I was confident that the patronus test would be different. I was goi=
ng to find out my magical spirit animal. My noble, inner beast. My equivale=
nt of a daemon from Philip Pullman=E2=80=99s <em><a href=3D"http://www.peng=
uinrandomhouse.com/books/215515/his-dark-materials-by-philip-pullman/" targ=
et=3D"_blank">Dark Materials</a></em> books.</p>
<p>So I took the test. I clicked on answers as quickly as I could. (They sa=
id they were measuring my reaction time.) I tried to give the answers that =
best reflected my inner self. And then the test was over.</p>
<p>I dragged my cursor across the screen to summon my patronus. (And I migh=
t=E2=80=99ve yelled out loud =E2=80=9CExpecto Patronum!=E2=80=9D when I did=
 it.) It started to materialize and=E2=80=A6</p>
<p><strong>My patronus was a polecat.</strong></p>
<p>A polecat.</p>
<p><em>Huh?</em></p>
<p>So, the first thing I did was Google =E2=80=9Cpolecat,=E2=80=9D because =
who the bleep knows what a polecat is?</p>
<p>When you Google =E2=80=9Cpolecat,=E2=80=9D this is the description that =
shows up at the top of the results page.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9Ca weasel-like Eurasian mammal=E2=80=A6=E2=80=9D (Weasel?)</p>
<p>=E2=80=9C=E2=80=A6 with mainly dark brown fur and a darker mask across t=
he eyes=E2=80=A6=E2=80=9D (Not so bad.)</p>
<p>=E2=80=9C=E2=80=A6noted for ejecting a <em>fetid fluid</em> when threate=
ned.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p>WHAT?</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CAnother term for skunk.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p>WHAT?!</p>
<p>My beautiful inner spirit animal is best known for =E2=80=9Cejecting a f=
etid fluid when threatened.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p>REALLY?</p>
<p>I don=E2=80=99t even care that it=E2=80=99s small. Like a scarab beetle =
or a flying squirrel=E2=80=A6 I=E2=80=99d be fine with those. But my extrem=
ely personal magical guardian, an animal defined by my very being, is a poo=
r man=E2=80=99s skunk who sprays poop water out of its own body?!</p>
<p>So, if I died suddenly and there was a wizard or a witch who was deeply =
in love with me, they=E2=80=99d have to assume my patronus as a tribute and=
, one day, someone would ask them, <em>=E2=80=9CSo you=E2=80=99ve had that =
patronus ever since Tom died?=E2=80=9D</em></p>
<p><em>=E2=80=9CYes.=E2=80=9D</em></p>
<p><em>=E2=80=9CA polecat? And you=E2=80=99re going to keep it?=E2=80=9D</e=
m></p>
<p><strong><em>=E2=80=9CAlways.=E2=80=9D</em></strong></p>
<p><em>=E2=80=9CReally?=E2=80=9D</em></p>
<p><em>(long pause) =E2=80=9CI mean, I didn=E2=80=99t really think it throu=
gh at the time=E2=80=A6=E2=80=9D</em></p>
<p>I am not going to lie. It was a blow. It was a harsh blow.</p>
<p>Everyone in my office was taking the test, and I should say I wasn=E2=80=
=99t the only one who wasn=E2=80=99t totally on board with their patronus. =
Someone got a salmon, another person was a field mouse. And there were lots=
 of cats. But you could tell that the general consensus was that NO ONE had=
 it worse than a polecat. My patronus existed, apparently, to make other pe=
ople feel better.</p>
<p>It turns out that patronus dissatisfaction was an internet wide phenomen=
on. Joss Whedon was inconsolable about having a weasel patronus. (Hey Joss,=
 does your weasel spray fetid fluid? No? Poor baby.) Others lamented that t=
hey didn=E2=80=99t receive the rare unicorn patronus. And <a href=3D"https:=
//twitter.com/jk_rowling/status/778942344523550720" target=3D"_blank">J.K. =
Rowling herself had to turn to Twitter</a> to convince people that rat and =
mole patronuses were actually pretty cool.</p>
<p>That was the moment that turned me around actually. Seeing the author of=
 some of my favorite books having to take time out of her day to sell a str=
anger on the merits of a rat patronus. It opened my eyes.</p>
<p><strong>We=E2=80=99re lucky.</strong></p>
<p>We=E2=80=99re all so lucky to have this brilliant, bizarre world of wiza=
rds and witches to play in. A woman created this magical universe out of no=
thing and gave it to the world in <a href=3D"http://harrypotter.scholastic.=
com/" target=3D"_blank">seven amazing books</a>, two stage-plays, some them=
e parks, and a whole bunch of movies.</p>
<p>Harry Potter shouldn=E2=80=99t be about wish fulfilment. It should be ab=
out letting your imagination run wild in one of the greatest literary sandb=
oxes ever created. And if that means I have to stretch the limits of my per=
sonal fantasy to make hanging out with a ghost polecat cool =E2=80=94 so be=
 it.</p>
<p>My patronus IS a polecat.</p>
<p>I=E2=80=99m just owning it now. If a Death Eater or Dementor ever comes =
at me, guess what they=E2=80=99re getting right in the face? That=E2=80=99s=
 right =E2=80=94&nbsp;FETID FLUID.</p>
<p>That=E2=80=99s a little bit more awesome than just getting attacked by a=
 claw or a tooth, am I right? That=E2=80=99s some Fred and George Weasley n=
onsense right there.</p>
<p>I have a weird, gross patronus and I LOVE IT.</p>
<p>So, let=E2=80=99s see some patronus pride, Potter fans. The world would =
be pretty boring if we were all lions and hippogriffs. Let=E2=80=99s proudl=
y venture out into the world with our odd little animal friends by our side=
, and show J.K. Rowling that we couldn=E2=80=99t be happier to be as unusua=
lly diverse as the literary world she created.</p>
<p>(But, seriously, a polecat? I win the =E2=80=9Cunfortunate patronus=E2=
=80=9D award, right?)</p>
